Perhaps the greatest problem in theoretical physics today is the problem of creating a consistent theory of quantum gravity.
That is, we'd like a theory that combines quantum mechanics, the theory of the very, very small scales, microscopic tiny scales,
with the theory of the very, very large cosmological scales, scales at which gravity becomes very important.
Gravity is governed by the theory of general relativity.
This has proven to be a very difficult problem and very little progress has been made in the last half of a century.
Because of a fundamental misunderstanding or incomplete understanding of the background in which these theories take place.
That is an understanding of space and time.
In quantum mechanics, the theory proceeds as if it's being conducted inside of a laboratory where there's some external measuring stick and clock available to measure positions and times.
Quantum mechanics is a very absolute Newtonian based theory.
It depends on a fixed non dynamical background structure. We use Minkowski space and quantum field theory.
And likewise time is given as just a parameter that uniformly and uniquely flows forward consistently throughout the universe.
But we know from general relativity that this is in fact not the case.
There is in fact no fixed space time background space time is governed by geometries that are in fact dynamic. They change with respect to time.
General relativity can be thought of as a relational theory in the sense that it's not space and time that are primary.
In fact, the events that occur within the theory that are the primary information the relevant information of the theory and space and time only exists as descriptions of the interrelations of these events.
These are fundamentally different viewpoints of the arenas in which these theories take place. And so, perhaps to make any further progress, what is required is a fundamental reinterpretation, or fundamental understanding of the metaphysical characteristics of space and time themselves.
Space time philosophy goes back centuries.
Godfrey Leibniz was a contemporary of Isaac Newton.
And he had a very relational perspective on the universe.
Central to his metaphysics were three principles, the principle of sufficient reason that for every fact there is a reason that is sufficient to explain what and why it is the way it is, and not otherwise.
The principle of the identity of indiscernible. If there is no way of telling two entities apart, then they are in fact one and the same thing. There is no difference if we have no way of telling them apart.
The principle that the complete notion of a contingent thing requires a knowledge of not only the thing itself, but everything in the universe in which it has a relation to.
A thing is not defined as a thing itself, but in its relations to the other things in the universe.
So in this sense, the universe should be thought of as a relational dynamical system.
This is the fundamental basis of a theory of shape dynamics.
Let's give some examples of what a relational universe would mean.
The relational universe space exists only as a relationship between the objects in the universe and has no existence, no ontological existence in and of itself, apart from the existence of those objects.
Again, it's a relationship.
Likewise, motion exists only as the relationship between those objects.
How the objects change.
Time, then, is simply a measure of the relative motions of objects.
And in fact, we know this to be the case. How do we tell the time? We tell the time with a clock.
The clock is simply the motion of moving hands around a dial, ultimately calibrated to the motion of the planets through the solar system, the earth around the sun.
Or if you like, in modern definitions, the motion of the vibration of a cesium atom.
So think about the relational universe through a number of thought experiments, these thought experiments using the three key principles of Leibniz can be thought of as arguments against an absolute theory of space and time.
