The question of time is in fact quite complex and deserves a little bit more discussion.
From a Newtonian absolute perspective, time is thought of as a real thing, an existent object.
But what is time? How do we measure time?
In physics, T, the parameter for time, is simply a parameter that monotonically increases.
And most of the laws of physics, interestingly, are in fact time invariant.
In other words, if we replace T with minus T in the equations, we end up with valid solutions to those same equations.
In fact, we get effectively the same solutions just in reverse.
The basic example is a bouncing ball influenced by gravity. Give it an initial upwards velocity. It's going to follow a parabolic trajectory, reaching some maximum height and falling back to the ground.
And just before it bounces, hitting the ground with some final velocity.
If we reverse time or rather replace time with negative time in the equations, what happens?
It's a reverse movie. Instead of a particle hitting the ground with velocity BF, it instead is shooting upwards from the ground with an initial velocity equal and opposite.
It then follows exactly the same trajectory, ending up with the same final velocity as the initial velocity we had given it in the previous picture.
And this idea of time invariance is in fact quite ubiquitous throughout physics, except for one notable exception.
This is the second law of thermodynamics.
In a statistical picture, as understood through Boltzmann statistics introduced by with Boltzmann.
Entropy, a measure of the disorder of a system always increases.
The second law of thermodynamics tells us that the entropy will always tend towards a maximum will always increase and this is indeed time asymmetric.
And because of this, the increase of entropy is oftentimes associated with an arrow of time.
Time is thought to proceed in the direction of the increase of entropy.
There are significant conceptual issues with this idea.
One of these is the fact that in order to increase an entropy, this implies that somewhere in the past, there must have been a very ordered low entropy system.
What created such a special initial condition.
This is something we'd like to understand.
Ernst Mach, the same Mach that is known for the Mach numbers supersonic travel was in fact a very wide read and wide studied physicist, and his ideas were in fact very influential to Einstein's development of the theory of general relativity.
Central to shape dynamics is so called Mach's principle, which says that local physical laws are determined by the large scale structure of the universe and depend only on directly observable quantities.
A physical laws cannot depend on things we can't see, only on the things that we can measure.
Shape dynamics is a theory constructed on this idea.
It was invented by Dr. Julian Barber.
And in his own words, shape dynamics is a theory of gravity that retains the essential dynamical core of general relativity, while removing in a well motivated way structure that is potentially redundant, and may well be responsible for the difficulties in the creation of quantum gravity.
In dynamics, we have dynamical systems that evolve as trajectories through the background that we will call shape space, the space of all possible shape configurations.
The principle of best matching is defined to is used to define an idea of distances and a natural metric in the theory.
Then a principle of least action can be used to find geodesics through this background.
