One step further from the general relativistic analog to a quantum gravity analog, which we might term Machian quantum gravity, and this would proceed by quantizing a theory of geometrodynamics using Wheeler-DeWitt canonical quantum gravity techniques.
The arena in which shape dynamics occurs is called shape space.
Shape space by definition, however, is background independent.
And in shape space, all absolute elements, vestiges of an absolute Newtonian space, are eliminated.
Shape space is unique because it is defined by the fewest possible observable initial data, and it is these data that will then determine the observable evolution of the system.
The only variables that we permit in our theory are those that describe the shapes of the instantaneous particle configurations.
And it is these shapes that are treated as our dynamical variables in the theory.
Shape space is the space of all possible configurations.
In shape space, time does not exist.
It is completely unobservable.
These observable, however, are the relative motions of the particles and more specifically the shapes in the system, and it is these dynamics that can be observed and perhaps reinterpreted as motion and time.
The simplest ways of describing a shape space is taking the sets of all interparticle distances between the particles in the theory, and it is these sets that can be considered the snapshots of the instantaneous shape configurations of the system.
However, distances are of course an absolute quantity and must be measured with respect to something else with some measuring stick.
What we would like are truly scale invariant variables in our theory.
So what we can do is create the idea of a scale invariant distance by dividing the interparticle distances by an overall scale factor, which we might call the root mean harmonic distance.
We can calculate it in a sense by summing over all of the interparticle distances squared in the theory.
In group theory, shape space is a reduction space of the larger Newtonian Cartesian space in which the Newtonian theory exists.
And in doing this reduction, we are in fact eliminating a level of redundant structure that is in fact unnecessary to describe the dynamics of the system.
We're getting rid of the redundant structure of absolute space.
If we start in the Cartesian space with n particles, the configuration space consists of three n dimensions, and that's because we have three degrees of freedom, say X, Y and Z positions for each particle.
But as we have discussed, there is redundant structure here.
So the first reduction that we will use is quotienting the Cartesian space by the group of translations. In other words, overall shifts of the system are redundant.
And quotienting by the translations brings us to what we would call quotient space in which we have eliminated three degrees of freedom and now are at dimension three and minus three.
And further quotient by overall rotations of the system, which again if there's nothing external with which to measure with respect to those rotations are invisible.
This again reduces the space by dimension three and brings us to what we might call configuration space.
To reach shape space, we also need to quotient by overall dilatations or changes of the overall scale of the configurations in the theory. This again reduces the dimension by one, bringing us to a dimension of three and minus seven.
In the general case, shape space requires seven less input data than the same theory to be described in a Newtonian background.
The simplest example of a shape space is for three particles, what we would call triangle space, because of course three point particles will always form some triangle.
In Cartesian space, we would need nine input data to describe the positions of each of the three particles.
But in shape space, we in fact only need nine minus seven or two datum to completely specify the configuration, the triangle.
This can be done in a number of different ways.
For example, we might choose one side of the triangle to be our quote unquote measuring stick set that equal to a distance of one in unit list variables, in which case we can measure the other two sides with respect to that one distance.
Perhaps better would be simply to use the angles within the triangle. And of course, the third angle within the triangle would be fixed by the geometry.
There are more sophisticated techniques, for example, the use of so called hop variables, as we will discuss in more detail moving forward.
And using these coordinations, we move to the expression of the shape space on the so called shapesphere, where every point on the surface of this sphere corresponds to a given configuration, ie, a specific triangle.
The equilateral triangle exists at the north and south poles, and the bilinear configurations exist along the equator.
