We'd like to eliminate some of that structure. And we can do so by constructing what we call the shape potential vis-a-vis.
This class really is the Newtonian potential, but multiplied by the square root of the center of mass moment of inertia in order to create a scale invariant quantity.
And it's important because now this shape potential gives rise to shape forces, which tell us only about the forces exerted on the system that change the configuration, or the shape of the system.
Related to this quantity, and in fact that in the negative of this quantity is a number that we will call the shape complexity.
The shape potential is a negative quantity.
Complexity then is just a positive number expressing the same relations, but it has a very important meaning in the theory. It tells us sensitively about the clustering of particles in the system.
Certain particles come close together. Of course, not only does the gravitational energy increase significantly, so will the complexity of the system.
But it does so in a way that is independent of the overall scale of the system itself.
Understanding shape space, we can then describe trajectories through this space.
And it's these trajectories that tell us the history of the dynamics. What has happened in the theory?
In Newtonian dynamics, we began in Cartesian space, and as time flows, the positions of those particles move, the position in that Cartesian space changes.
And we can think of this as a monotonically increasing curve, rising with a monotonically increasing time parameter.
But as we have argued, time is in fact invisible, relational.
So it is actually the curve itself projected down into the Cartesian configuration space that tells us the history of the entire system.
And that, of course, can be parameterized in any number of different ways, but the history is in fact there and existent at all times.
We'd like to make the further reduction from this Cartesian space into the shape space, because it is this shape space history, or the shape space curve rather, that tells us the truly observable history of the system.
In practice, carrying out this reduction, or this projection into the shape space, involves imposing a number of constraints on the Newtonian system.
Namely, we would like to eliminate translations, rotations, and dilatations from the system.
This is illustrated in these top triangles. In picture one, you'll notice particles A, B, and C have moved ever so slightly from their initial position represented by the gray triangle.
The dotted triangle, the dash triangle, is just a slightly different shape, a slightly different configuration from that first triangle.
You'll notice in the diagram labeled by T, that we have that same dash triangle only shifted over to the right just a little bit.
In a Newtonian Cartesian space, these would be unique motions, but they would be invisible from a shape space perspective.
Likewise, if we rotate that dash triangle relative to the original triangle in R, or scale that triangle, making a bigger triangle or dilating it, as represented in graphic D,
all of these motions would be invisible and reduced in the shape space.
So we're going to constrain these motions. We're not going to allow them. We're going to set them to zero from the get-go.
We can do so by putting the triangle at the center of mass, and requiring that the center of mass momentum is zero, so that the particle is not translating.
Likewise, we will require that the angular momentum is zero, eliminating overall rotations of the system.
And finally, we might require that the dilatational momentum, or rather the time rate of change of the center of mass moment of inertia, which tells us about the overall scale of the system, we might require that to be zero as well.
Now, this last one turns out to be a bit tricky, and we may say more about it later on.
The changes of scale and dilatation do in fact have a very significant effect on the trajectories and the dynamics of the theory itself.
In the shape space perspective, all of these different motions, translations, rotations, and dilatations, give rise to different Newtonian initial velocities, but again are all collapsed to the same position in a shape space.
There's one more condition that we need to impose, and that's setting the total energy of the system to zero.
And this is because the total energy is the sum of the kinetic and the potential, but any redefinition of time will affect only the kinetic energy and not the potential and therefore change the value of your energy.
Thus, the only scale invariant choice is to set the energy to zero so that these two quantities perfectly cancel each other out.
