Let's imagine a universe of just a few particles, each with a mass position and velocity relative to the others.
Isaac Newton described their motion in absolute time, which he said flows uniformly forward.
Given the particles positions and velocities at an initial time, his equations determine how the particles move ever after solving the equations when the particles exert gravitational forces on each other is the end body problem, where N is the number of particles.
Because Newton's equations are symmetric in time, we can, keeping the initial positions fixed, reverse all the velocities and find the motions in the opposite direction.
Because time is not visible, and we consider the particles to be the whole universe. There is nothing that distinguishes one direction of Newton's absolute time from the other.
The measure of mass moment of inertia ICM measures the size of the end body system.
If the total energy is either zero or positive, then except in a very special case, we won't consider the size always has a unique finite minimum value from which it increases to infinity in both directions of time.
You can see how the instantaneous size changes in the spot. First going in one direction, and then the other.
On both sides of Newton's absolute time zero, the system is similar and appears time invariant.
Julian Barber has called this point of minimum size, the Janus point. Around it, the distribution of the particles is more uniform than elsewhere, becoming more clustered in both directions away from it.
To better define it, a Janus point is a point where the size of an end body system is at a minimum, and all solutions where the energy is non negative.
If there were positive energy in the system, all particles would shoot off into infinity. If there was negative energy, the potential energy would be greater than the kinetic, and the system would collapse in on itself.
The end body universe expands to infinite size becomes more clustered in both directions away from the Janus point.
The blustering defines bi-directional arrows of time. The Roman gods standing at the Janus point could look in opposite directions of time simultaneously.
